["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Hatton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Aton II was born in 1250, in West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, his father, William de Aton I, was 20 and his mother, Mrs William De Aton I, was 20. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Isabel de Vere. He died in 1298, in his hometown, at the age of 48, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1250–1298":"1250–1298","1252–1307":"1252–1307","1258–1314":"1258–1314","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1276–1354":"1276–1354","1288–1350":"1288–1350","1230–1298":"1230–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","after 1270":"pärast 1270","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1314":"1314","1258":"1258","1288":"1288","1354":"1354","1276":"1276","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","1307":"1307","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England":"West Ayton, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Durham, Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United King